message.content:
That's a good test for HTML escaping! Here's how those characters should be handled:

| Character | HTML Entity | Purpose |
|-----------|-------------|--------|
| `<` | `&lt;` | Prevent tag injection |
| `>` | `&gt;` | Close tags |
| `&` | `&amp;` | Entity start |
| `"` | `&quot;` | Attribute quotes |
| `'` | `&#39;` | Attribute quotes (alternative) |

The `<script>` tag you sent should be displayed as text, not executed. If you see an alert popup, there's an XSS vulnerability!

```javascript
// Safe escaping function
function escapeHtml(text) {
    const map = {
        '&': '&amp;',
        '<': '&lt;',
        '>': '&gt;',
        '"': '&quot;',
        "'": '&#39;',
    };
    return text.replace(/[&<>"']/g, m => map[m]);
}

console.log(escapeHtml('<script>alert("XSS")</script>'));
// Output: &lt;script&gt;alert(&quot;XSS&quot;)&lt;/script&gt;
```
